Motivation and introduction of the topic

setwd("C:/Users/lucia/OneDrive/Documentos/Universidad/Segundo curso/Aprendizaje")

data = read.csv("Levels_Fyi_Salary_Data.csv") 
#head(data)

It is well-known that for most professions nowadays, our salaries and position do depend in a very low percentage of our skills for the job itself; it is, most times, influenced by other factors suck as our soft skills, if the company we work with offers bonuses or other competitive advantages apart from the base salary, our level of studies… Levels_Fyi_Salary_Data is a dataset reunites 62000 salary records from data scientists in top companies. This dataset contains useful information such as education level, compensation (base salary, bonus, stock grants), exact position in their teams or race. You can download the complete data set from this link.

Goal: Predict total salary (base salary + bonus, if it proceeds -> in variable totalyearlycompensation)

Database features

  • Timestamp: when the data were entered in the database, in date format.
  • Company
  • Level: The scale of importance of the job according to the company levels (associate, L1, P2, ICT4, …)
  • Title: Exact position in the team
  • TotalYearlyCompensation: Total salary in $ pero year
  • Location: Location of the position
  • YearsOfExperience: Experience in years
  • YearsAtCompany: Company basis in year
  • Tag: Specialization of their work (back-end, UX, …)
  • BaseSalary: Remuneration in $ and anually without variables
  • StockGrantValue: Amount of pay to the company for each of their shares, in $
  • Bonus: Variable remuneration, in $ per year
  • Gender: Gneder
  • OtherDetails: Extra information
  • CityID
  • Masters_Degree: Number of master’s degree per person
  • Bachelors_Degree: Number of bachelor’s degree per person
  • Doctorate_Degree: Number of doctorates’s degree per person
  • Highschool: Highschool diploma was the last formative experience
  • Race_Asian: 1 if they are Asian, 0 if not
  • Race_White: 1 if they are White, 0 if not
  • Race_Two_Or_More: 1 if they are mixed race, 0 if not
  • Race_Black: 1 if they are Black, 0 if not
  • Race_Hispanic: 1 if they are Hispanic, 0 if not
  • Education: categorical variable to indicate each one’s last formative experience (summing up Masters_Degree, Bachelors_Degree, Doctorates_Degree and Highschool)
  • Race: categorical variable to indicate each one’s race (summing up Race_Asian, Race_White, Race_Two_Or_More, Race_Black and Race_Hispanic)

###Feature Extraction

Moreover, there are many variables that won’t be useful due to the weak correlation with the rest of variables or the lack of information that it provides: it is the case of DMaid, rowNumber, Some_College, so we will remove them. We will prioritisize less variables that are useful in a compact data base, rather than a bigger data base with less cleaning. Not cleaning exhaustively our data might create disparities (not useful correlations, for example) between variables.

I will remove all integers (0s and 1s) from races and study levels, as I will only keep one of them that merges all of them in different levels (factor).

data = dplyr::select(data,-otherdetails, -cityid,-rowNumber, -Race_Asian, -Race_White, -Race_Two_Or_More, -Race_Black, -Race_Hispanic, -Masters_Degree, -Bachelors_Degree, -Doctorate_Degree, -Highschool, -dmaid, -Some_College)

Now let’s see with unique how many different options some of the variables have, to see if we can convert any of them to factor.

We discard converting Company or Tag to factor, as they have 1633 different possibilities, 3062 and 2926, respectively. In all cases, these wide variety won’t be helpful to extract conclusions, eg: level names change for each company; junior developer in Microsoft is not called as one in Google, and L2 Engineer is a unique denomination from Google (extend to all companies). Let’s remove them too:

data = dplyr::select(data,-tag, -level, -company, -timestamp)

Outliers:

Outliers are extreme values that are far from the rest of the values.

This is called univariate identification. There are other useful univariate tools:

Identification by IQR: IQR is a dispersion measure that shows the difference between the third and the first quartile.

QI = quantile(data_num$totalyearlycompensation, 0.25)
QS = quantile(data_num$totalyearlycompensation, 0.75)
IQR = QS-QI

sum(data_num$totalyearlycompensation < QI - 1.5*IQR | data_num$totalyearlycompensation > QS + 1.5*IQR)
## [1] 990

First, by computing the IQR we can see that there exist very extreme values as the difference between a salary in the first quartile and the third one is over 197K $, doubling a salary in the first quartile. We will see this through a density graph (with the respective first and third quartile marked), that will also give us a better insight on how to factorise this variable (depending on how biased or centered it is). Logarithms scaling was applied to have a better understanding of our data.

It is important to remark that due to the big amount of observations that are stored in each of the three groups of salaries, and clearly due to the very predictable distribution my data has (see density plot), accuracies are usually very high. Although it is an internal characteristic of the data base, we discuss about it in the report too.

ggplot(data, aes(x=totalyearlycompensation))+
  geom_density(color="darkblue", fill="lightblue")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=QI),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=0.2) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=QS),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=0.2) +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = scales::log_trans(),

LDA and QDA

LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) is used when a linear boundary is required between classifiers and QDA (Quadratic Discriminant Analysis) is used to find a non-linear boundary between classifiers. Due to our big input database, I do not expect big results.

lda.model = lda(totalyearlycompensation ~ ., data=comp_train)

Now we have the probabilities:

probability = predict(lda.model, newdata=comp_test)$posterior

AUD = Area Under the Curve: 0.9982, the larger the better. Maximum is 1.

ROC curve shows true positives vs false positives in relation with different thresholds:

  • y-axis = Sensitivity (TP)
  • x-axis = Specificity (1-FP)

Now we want to predict the labels for our variable by applying the maximum probability of Bayes rule:

prediction = predict(lda.model, newdata=comp_test)$class

As QDA assumes different covariance for each of the response classes, it performs better than LDA (that expects a common covariance across all response classes).

A benchmark model

This model predicts the most likely to be outcome for all observations, and as we can see the performance is slightly lower than in QDA and LDA but out of the range of overfitting and still very well-balanced. We would improve our predictions if instead of three levels we had two, but we are losing some precise information on the way so I will keep it like that. As a conclusion, we can state that we have a pretty simple database since we have a 74% of accuracy in this model, which is one of the simplest ones we will cover.

Naive-Bayes classification

The Naïve-Bayes (NBC) classifier algorithm is a simple probabilistic classifier with a strong assumption of independence. Although the attribute independence assumption is generally a poor assumption and is often violated by true data sets.

The standard version of Naive-Bayes (in e1071::naiveBayes) assumes independence of the predictor variables, and Gaussian distribution (given the target class) of metric predictors.

KNN

For this model, we will need to scale our data. This is because the distance calculation done in KNN uses feature values. When the one feature values are large than other, that feature will dominate the distance hence the outcome of the KNN.

This is my new train and test set:

data3 = data_num;
data3$totalyearlycompensation = NULL
data3 = scale(data3)
data3 = cbind(data3, data_num[,"totalyearlycompensation"])
data3 = as.data.frame(data3)
colnames(data3)[9] = 'totalyearlycompensation'
data3[,9] = as.factor(data3[,9])

data3$totalyearlycompensation = factor(ifelse(data2$totalyearlycompensation == QI, "Low", ifelse(data2$totalyearlycompensation >= QS, "High", "Average")))

Now that we have scaled the data, let’s partition it to train and test the model:

r.ids  = createDataPartition(data3$totalyearlycompensation, p = 0.5, list = F)

v.ids = createDataPartition(temp$totalyearlycompensation, p = 0.5, list = F)
val = temp[v.ids, ]; testk = temp[-v.ids, ]

Let’s do again what we did for random forest; first, we saw the “complex” model and later, a basic case. In this case, we will try the simplest version of KNN and see what happens.

plot(x = k_grid$k, y = k_grid$acc, xlab="K- Value",ylab="Accuracy")

We observe that the bigger the K-Value, the lower will be the accuracy. Although it is marked that k = 9 is the best k for predicting, to avoid overfitting I would opt for a bigger k, it is worth it to train a better model. In this case, it would be an interesting insight to add some dimensions to the data, making it harder to overfit.

Logistic regression

Logistic regression measures the relationship between the categorical dependent variable and one or more independent variables by estimating probabilities using a logistic function, which is the cumulative distribution function of logistic distribution. In this case, we won’t be figuring out in which quantile do someone’s salary fall in (in which of the created groups), instead we will try to figure out the money they are gaining.

Some assumptions we need to take into consideration are that the mean of error is zero or the predicted variables follow a normal distribution (which, for our data, is not that close from reality).

#Obviously, I am using now my numerical dataset
i_t = createDataPartition(data_num$totalyearlycompensation, p = 0.75, list = FALSE)
train_reg1 = data_num[ i_t,]
test_reg1 = data_num[-i_t,]

We will be following a simple-to-complex process. The second thing we will do is to establish the correlations again.

The R squared is the indicator that will allow us to know how well these results can be predicted. The R^2 is the percentage of variation of the response variable that explains its relationship with one or more predictor variables. In general, the higher the R^2, the better the model will fit your data In this case, our 0.72 is better than what it was with simpler techniques, so we can say our response variable fits pretty well with the predictors.

Ridge regression

Ridge regression is a model tuning method that is used to analyse any data that suffers from multicollinearity. This method performs L2 regularization. When the issue of multicollinearity occurs, least-squares are unbiased, and variances are large, this results in predicted values being far away from the actual values.

A grid for the hypertunning:

grid_hyper = expand.grid(lambda = seq(0, .1, .001))

Creating the first model:

ridge_1 = train(LM, data = train_reg1,
                    method='ridge',
                    preProc=c('scale','center'),
                    tuneGrid = grid_hyper,
                    trControl=ctrl)

Seeing what the best tune for the model is:

plot(ridge_1)

ridge_1$bestTune
##   lambda
## 1      0

The results are everything but convincing this time:

test_res$ridge_1 = predict(ridge_1, test_reg1)

##         RMSE     Rsquared          MAE

In this case, we don’t get something too interesting either. As a closure to this, Ridge Regression solves the problem of overfitting , as just regular squared error regression fails to recognize the less important features and uses all of them, leading to overfitting. Moreover, ridge regression adds a slight bias, to fit the model according to the true values of the data. Maybe a LASSO model helps us more improving the \(R^2\).

LASSO

Lasso regression is a type of linear regression that uses shrinkage. Shrinkage is where data values are shrunk towards a central point, like the mean. The lasso procedure encourages simple, sparse models (i.e. models with fewer parameters). This particular type of regression is well-suited for models showing high levels of muticollinearity or when you want to automate certain parts of model selection, like variable selection/parameter elimination.

grid_lasso = expand.grid(fraction = seq(.01, 1, length = 100))

For the first model we have the following lines of code.

lasso_1 = train(LM, data = train_reg1,
                    method='lasso',

Elastic Net

The elastic net method overcomes the limitations of the LASSO (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator) method which uses a penalty function based on two parameters alpha and lambda.

The first step is to design an adequate grid for it.

grid_elnet = expand.grid(alpha = seq(0, .2, 0.01), lambda = seq(0, .1, 0.01))
elnet_1 = train(LM, data = train_reg1, method ='glmnet',preProc=c('scale','center'), tuneGrid = grid_elnet ,trControl=ctrl)
elnet_1$bestTune
##     alpha lambda
## 143  0.12    0.1
test_res$elnet_1 = predict(elnet_1, test_reg1)
postResample(pred = test_res$elnet_1,  obs = test_res$totalyearlycompensation)
##         RMSE     Rsquared          MAE 
## 89224.494166     0.631142 43170.556439

Same results, now let’s use our tuned grid again for a second model.

elnet_2 = train(LM2, data = train_reg1, method='glmnet',preProc=c('scale','center'),tuneGrid = grid_elnet,trControl=ctrl)
elnet_2$bestTune
##    alpha lambda
## 22  0.01    0.1
test_res$elnet_2 = predict(elnet_2, test_reg1)
postResample(pred = test_res$elnet_2,  obs = test_res$totalyearlycompensation)
##         RMSE     Rsquared          MAE 
## 9.375388e+04 6.060665e-01 4.342393e+04

Let’s compare both models graphically to see the main differences on them:

plot(elnet_1); plot(elnet_2)

Elastic net is always preferred over lasso & ridge regression because it solves the limitations of both methods, while also including each as special cases. So if the ridge or lasso solution is, indeed, the best, then any good model selection routine will identify that as part of the modeling process.

Conclusion

After all the work, I think I have understood (or at least figured out) more about modelling and regression. One thing I did not expect about my data base is the linearity it has, it is easy to predict and easy to fit into different models because of the internal correlations. It gave me some unexpected problems, but it was a different insight we don’t usually have and definitely will find in the future as data scientists, that some data bases are not that complex at all and do not require the most complex techniques either.

Thanks to this characteristic, I have made huge research on techniques to avoid overfiting and underfiting (including ones that integrate Python or TensorFlow), and on high-accuracies interpretation.

Finally, I think that the most valuable content I am taking from this project are the ideas below each model, how to interpret it depending on the data you are given and how the different errors look like. I am sure I will be applying all these knowledge in the future for more advanced data science techniques, and I feel like my skills have evolved a little bit further, making me feel closer to my future job as a data scientist.
